## Opinion and Conclusion

Based on the comprehensive review of the available data and expert analyses, it is evident that beauty pageants pose significant risks to the mental health of participants, especially children and adolescents. The emphasis on physical appearance and the culture of judgment foster body dissatisfaction, low self-esteem, and increase the likelihood of eating disorders and other psychological problems.

While some positive aspects such as skill development and confidence-building are noted, these benefits are often contingent upon conforming to unrealistic and potentially harmful beauty standards. The psychological damage, including long-term mental health consequences, outweighs the purported advantages.

Therefore, it is crucial for parents, educators, and policymakers to critically evaluate the role of beauty pageants in society and consider reforms or alternatives that prioritize holistic development over superficial beauty. Mental health support and education about body positivity should be integral to any participation in such events.

